{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619106","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619106"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:29:16+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:29:16+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16539"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16539","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16539"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9230"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75409"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9230"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16539"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60919"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4904"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"7146"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21873"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21877"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75409","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75409"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe cerebellum can be divided into three functional zones: medial (vermis), intermediate (paravermal), and lateral (hemispheric) regions. Each zone has distinct connections and functions in motor control.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of the intermediate (paravermal) zone of the cerebellum?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Controls voluntary movement planning","Coordinates proximal limb and trunk movements","Maintains balance and posture","Controls fine finger movements","Coordinates eye movements"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecoordinates proximal limb and trunk movements\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary function of the intermediate (paravermal) zone of the cerebellum. This region receives input from the spinocerebellar tracts and projects to the rubrospinal and corticospinal systems, allowing it to coordinate movements of proximal muscles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControls voluntary movement planning\u003C/strong\u003E is managed by the lateral (hemispheric) zone, which connects with the cerebral cortex via pontine nuclei\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintains balance and posture\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily controlled by the medial zone (vermis), which receives vestibular input\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EControls fine finger movements\u003C/strong\u003E is managed by the lateral cerebellar hemisphere\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECoordinates eye movements\u003C/strong\u003E is primarily managed by the flocculonodular lobe\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding these functional zones helps localise cerebellar lesions. Damage to the intermediate zone typically results in ipsilateral limb ataxia, while vermis damage causes truncal ataxia and gait disturbance.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["The intermediate (paravermal) zone of the cerebellum primarily coordinates proximal limb and trunk movements.","The cerebellum has three functional zones: medial (balance), intermediate (proximal limb/trunk), and lateral (motor planning/fine movements).","Each cerebellar zone receives distinct inputs and projects to different areas of the motor system."],"references":["Sullivan EV. Cognitive functions of the cerebellum. Neuropsychol Rev. 2010 Sep;20(3):227-8. doi: 10.1007/s11065-010-9144-8. Epub 2010 Sep 2. PMID: 20811946; PMCID: PMC4723423","Gillig PM, Sanders RD. Psychiatry, neurology, and the role of the cerebellum. Psychiatry (Edgmont). 2010 Sep;7(9):38-43. PMID: 20941351; PMCID: PMC2952646","Hall, J. E., \u0026 Hall, M. E. (2020). Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book: Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2024). Textbook of Clinical Neuroanatomy-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Michael-Titus, A. T., \u0026 Shortland, P. (2022). The Nervous System, E-Book: The Nervous System, E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60919"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16539"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60919"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T19:34:37+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-29T22:24:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9230"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75409"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici